{
  "text": "In response to infections and injuries, however, HMGB1 is secreted from activated immune cells or passively released from injured cells. Excessive HMGB1 secretion/release adversely contributes to the pathogenesis of infectionand injury-elicited inflammatory diseases. For instance, in animal models of endotoxemia or sepsis (induced by cecal ligation and puncture, CLP), HMGB1-neutralizing antibodies improve survival [CITATION_1] and rescue rodents from lethal sepsis even if given at 24 h after CLP [CITATION_2] 8] . Similarly, HMGB1-specific antibodies are protective against ischemia/reperfusion [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , trauma [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , chemical toxemia [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , atherosclerosis [CITATION_11] , gastric ulcer [CITATION_12] , and hyperoxia [CITATION_13] , supporting the pathogenic role of HMGB1 in injury-elicited inflammatory diseases. Furthermore, in animal models of rheumatoid arthritis, anti-HMGB1 agents confer significant protection against joint tissue edema [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] , supporting a pathogenic role for HMGB1 in autoimmune diseases. The establishment of HMGB1 as a mediator of various inflammatory diseases has prompted the search for inhibitors that can attenuate HMGB1 secretion or action. In this review, we summarize the divergent mechanisms by which several herbal therapies effectively inhibit active HMGB1 secretion and action and hope to stimulate interests ",
